The only tangible help the Saudis gave Kuwait was to shelter Kuwait's ruling family and  to allow the Kuwaitis to briefly operate a radio that broadcast resistance messages.
Saudi  Arabia, fearing Iraqi reprisal, would not take the potent action of closing the pipeline that  carries Iraqi oil for export across Saudi Arabia to the Red Sea.
Turkey also ducked  President Bush's suggestion that they cut their pipeline taking Iraqi oil to the  Mediterranean.
The Saudi's made a joint statement with the Gulf Cooperation Council  condemning the invasion and were one of 14 members of the 21-member Arab League to  issue condemnation. 
